ly Ghost, and Contemplations on the Dread and Love of God. Demonstrating that these texts actually provided alternative—and more appealing—notions of gender than those authorized by the Church, Bartlett redefines women's participation in medieval culture in terms of far greater agency and empowerment than have generally been acknowledged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAuthorshipxSex differences. 0aDevotional literature, English (Middle)xMale authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish prose literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aMimesis in literature. 0aSubjectivity in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezEnglandxHistory. 0aWomenxBooks and readingzEnglandxHistory. 0aWomenxPrayers and devotionsxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172208040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501722080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501722080/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK